messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

Full path
- /printshops/{printShopId}/reviews/{reviewId}

All HTTP methods acceptable?
- false

Acceptable methods (based on code)
- HEAD: false
- POST: false
- OPTIONS: false
- TRACE: false
- GET: false
- PUT: true
- DELETE: true
- PATCH: false

Explanation
- The deletePrintShopReview method is annotated with:
  @RequestMapping(value = "/printshops/{printShopId}/reviews/{reviewId}", method = RequestMethod.DELETE)
  which maps DELETE requests for the path "/printshops/{printShopId}/reviews/{reviewId}".
- The same path is also mapped by editPrintShopReview:
  @RequestMapping(value = "/printshops/{printShopId}/reviews/{reviewId}", method = RequestMethod.PUT)
  so PUT is also explicitly accepted for this exact path.
- The controller class has no class-level @RequestMapping, so there is no additional prefix; the full path is exactly the method-level value.
- No mapping in the code explicitly accepts HEAD, OPTIONS, TRACE, GET, POST or PATCH for this path. Per the instructions I only considered explicit code mappings (not runtime framework defaults), so those methods are marked false.
- "All HTTP methods acceptable" is false because the mappings specify specific methods (PUT and DELETE) rather than allowing all methods.
